<subSubSection id="78A66A299618FAE99DB0C2C8E215E8B6" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="biology">
<paragraph id="8446179F250286C6E72E7683601A6C5A" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="53FF01E8CD1812A4F1B925C5E5171998" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
The gallery has been reported as very confused and undecipherable. Larvae were reported boring in the wood. In addition, the species did not appear to colonize healthy trees (
<bibRefCitation id="560EE4C23A9C1E4D9D2B5F868D3B4863" author="Packard, AS" journalOrPublisher="U. S. Department of Agriculture" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" title="Insects injurious to forest and shade trees" year="1890">Packard 1890</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="E70A594A2088292EF49205F62B32649D" author="Smith, SM" editor="Cognato, AI" journalOrPublisher="Zookeys" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" pagination="35 - 43" title="Notes on Scolytusfagi Walsh 1867 with the designation of a neotype, distribution notes and a key to Scolytus Geoffroy of America east of the Mississippi River (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Scolytinae: Scolytini)." volume="56" volumeTitle="Sixty years of discovering scolytine and platypodine diversity: A tribute to Stephen L. Wood." year="2010 a">Smith and Cognato (2010a)</bibRefCitation>
summarized all information known about this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DE1EDF80267DE115C4239945E179E8BF" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="EA0489987EAFBC00E26D0AC2EE1F9214" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="53A7662508C2EA0761BDD54F2DFC5B8A" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
This species is very rarely encountered. Most museum collections occurred in the early 1900's and most recent collections have been from Lindgren funnel traps. There are many gaps in the known distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="FB820618269CCC531EAF58291C600C13" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Scolytus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scolytus fagi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fagi">Scolytus fagi</taxonomicName>
but the species likely occurs throughout the eastern US associated with its host trees.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
